\par \tab Sections are unique, with a few exceptions. All unique sections are 
\par \tab IDs, and are attached to either DIV or TABLE  elements in the 
\par \tab template file. 
\par 
\par \tab A section may be the child of another section, but must be the child of
\par \tab a category 2 user class. It can never be the child of a category 4 or 5
\par \tab class.
\par \tab 
\par \tab Sections are responsible for grouping elements and defining where 
\par \tab they should be positioned on the page. Defining section layouts 
\par \tab should be the bulk of any layout CSS, though the same sections will 
\par \tab also be defined for style in the style CSS. Positioning may be done 
\par \tab in either absolute or relative terms.
\par 
\par \tab Section styles should not be defined in relation to other sections. 
\par \tab Doing so will lead to brittle definitions that will break on different 
\par \tab template definitions.
\par 
\par \tab If you are programming the default templates for a module that is 
\par \tab sufficiently different as to require its own style, first consider whether 
\par \tab it will be sufficient to use the defined "default" style class, 
\par \tab .gsOtherSection. In the vast majority of cases, this will be more than
\par \tab adequate. If not, go ahead and specify an appropriate section class of 
\par \tab the format gsXxxxx. Most appropriately defined themes should apply
\par \tab a default styling, and you can contact the G2 theme team to have your
\par \tab style eventually added to the offically sanctioned set. See section on 
\par \tab defaults for more information.
