\par \tab Boxes are the smallest of the "container" categories. They're intended 
\par \tab to be used to contain small groups logically of related element and to
\par \tab also provide styling such as borders, spacing, etc.
\par 
\par \tab Boxes themselves may be nested inside each other, but all boxes are
\par \tab children of category 3 sections and not children of category 5 items.
\par \tab When refering to a box-level class definition in a non-global manner, 
\par \tab define it with respect to the categories above it rather than through its 
\par \tab relationships to other boxes or items.
\par 
\par \tab When giving the boxes positioning, it's better to use relative
\par \tab positions and let the sections determine the flow of the page. As
\par \tab many boxes are defined in terms of what section they are in, it would 
\par \tab be confusing to have a box that is logically contained in a section but
\par \tab physically outside it.\tab 
\par 
\par \tab Since boxes are used for so many different purposes, it is difficult to
\par \tab make one generic default. Instead, thoughtful theme designers should 
\par \tab define defaults based on the section the box appears in. For example:
\par 
\par \tab \tab #gsHeader div \{ /* default box in header section */ \}
\par \tab \tab #gsFooter div \{ /* default box in footer section */ \}
