\par 2.6.3\tab A NOTE ON DEFAULTS
\par 
\par \tab There are two kinds of defaults in use. The simpler default is a simple
\par \tab class that follows the format 'gxXxxOtherXxx.' These defaults are used 
\par \tab when the template designer accepts a generic format as acceptable,
\par \tab in the case of gsOther; or when there is a need for a common default, 
\par \tab as in the case of giThumbOther.
\par 
\par \tab Any theme should make sure to define these defaults.
\par 
\par \tab The second kind of default is used to define *undefined* <div> 
\par \tab elements. This is done by used the CSS selectors. For example,
\par \tab a default section can be defined:
\par 
\par \tab \tab #guAdmin > div, #guAdmin > div, #guAdmin > div, \{
\par \tab \tab \tab /* default definitions here */
\par \tab \tab \}
\par 
\par \tab This causes all undefined <div> elements that are direct children of
\par \tab a category 2 User to follow this default behavior. Here is one benifit of
\par \tab using this hierarchical structure of classes--since the div is a childe of
\par \tab a category 2 User, we can assume it is a yet-undefined category 3 
\par \tab Section. Similarly, the following definition is for a default box in the 
\par \tab header or footer sections:
\par 
\par \tab \tab #gsHeader > div, #gsFooter div \{
\par \tab \tab \tab /* default definitions here */
\par \tab \tab \}
\par 
\par \tab Theme designers are asked to at least provide a default Section and 
\par \tab Box element. A good theme should recognize when sections are 
\par \tab sufficiently different to require a differently formatted box, and to 
\par \tab define appropriate contextual defaults.
\par 
\par \tab In most cases, the second type of default shouldn't be needed. 
\par \tab However, defining them anyway adds flexibily for using ill-defined or 
\par \tab adventurously extended templates. In particular, defining a default 
\par \tab section allows for old templates to offer some support to new G2 
\par \tab modules.
